# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chroma-subsampling
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] It is used in many video and still image encoding schemes – both analog and digital – including in JPEG encoding.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Digital signals are often compressed to reduce file size and save transmission time.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Since the human visual system is much more sensitive to variations in brightness than color, a video system can be optimized by devoting more bandwidth to the luma component (usually denoted Y'), than to the color difference components **Cb** and **Cr**.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] In compressed images, for example, the 4:2:2 Y'CbCr scheme requires two-thirds the bandwidth of non-subsampled "4:4:4" R'G'B'.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] This reduction results in almost no visual difference as perceived by the viewer.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] The human vision system processes color information (hue and colorfulness) at about a third of the resolution of luminance (lightness/darkness information in an image).
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Therefore it is possible to sample color information at a lower resolution while maintaining good image quality.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] This is achieved by encoding RGB image data into a composite black and white image, with separated color difference data (chroma).
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] For example with $Y'C_{b}C_{r}$ , gamma encoded $R'G'B'$ components are weighted and then summed together to create the luma $Y'$ component.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] The color difference components are created by subtracting two of the weighted $R'G'B'$ components from the third.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] A variety of filtering methods can be used to limit the resolution.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Gamma encoded luma $Y'$ should not be confused with linear luminance Y .
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] The presence of gamma encoding is denoted with the prime symbol ' .
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Gamma-correcting electro-optical transfer functions (EOTF) are used due to the nonlinear response of human vision.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] The use of gamma improves perceived signal-to-noise in analogue systems, and allows for more efficient data encoding in digital systems.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] This encoding uses more levels for darker colors than for lighter ones, accommodating human vision sensitivity.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] The subsampling scheme is commonly expressed as a three-part ratio *J*:*a*:*b* (e.g.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] 4:2:2) or four parts, if alpha channel is present (e.g.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] 4:2:2:4), that describe the number of luminance and chrominance samples in a conceptual region that is *J* pixels wide and 2 pixels high.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] This notation is not valid for all combinations and has exceptions, e.g.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] 4:1:0 (where the height of the region is not 2 pixels, but 4 pixels, so if 8 bits per component are used, the media would be 9 bits per pixel) and 4:2:1.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] The mapping examples given are only theoretical and for illustration.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Also the diagram does not indicate any chroma filtering, which should be applied to avoid aliasing.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] To calculate required bandwidth factor relative to 4:4:4 (or 4:4:4:4), one needs to sum all the factors and divide the result by 12 (or 16, if alpha is present).
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Each of the three Y'CbCr components has the same sample rate, thus there is no chroma subsampling.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] This scheme is sometimes used in high-end film scanners and cinematic post-production.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] "4:4:4" may instead be wrongly referring to R'G'B' color space, which implicitly also does not have any chroma subsampling (except in JPEG R'G'B' can be subsampled).
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Formats such as HDCAM SR can record 4:4:4 R'G'B' over dual-link HD-SDI.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] The two chroma components are sampled at half the horizontal sample rate of luma: the horizontal chroma resolution is halved.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] This reduces the bandwidth of an uncompressed video signal by one-third, which means for 8 bit per component without alpha (24 bit per pixel) only 16 bits are enough, as in NV16.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] In 4:1:1 chroma subsampling, the horizontal color resolution is quartered, and the bandwidth is halved compared to no chroma subsampling.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Initially, 4:1:1 chroma subsampling of the DV format was not considered to be broadcast quality and was only acceptable for low-end and consumer applications.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] However, DV-based formats (some of which use 4:1:1 chroma subsampling) have been used professionally in electronic news gathering and in playout servers.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] DV has also been sporadically used in feature films and in digital cinematography.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] However, in most equipment, especially cheap TV sets and VHS/Betamax VCRs, the chroma channels have only the 0.5 MHz bandwidth for both **Cr** and **Cb** (or equivalently for I/Q).
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Thus the DV system actually provides a superior color bandwidth compared to the best composite analog specifications for NTSC, despite having only 1/4 of the chroma bandwidth of a "full" digital signal.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] In 4:2:0, the horizontal sampling is doubled compared to 4:1:1, but as the **Cb** and **Cr** channels are only sampled on each alternate line in this scheme, the vertical resolution is halved.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] This fits reasonably well with the PAL color encoding system, since this has only half the vertical chrominance resolution of NTSC.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] It would also fit extremely well with the SECAM color encoding system, since like that format, 4:2:0 only stores and transmits one color channel per line (the other channel being recovered from the previous line).
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] However, little equipment has actually been produced that outputs a SECAM analogue video signal.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] In general, SECAM territories either have to use a PAL-capable display or a transcoder to convert the PAL signal to SECAM for display.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] There are four main variants of 4:2:0 schemes, having different horizontal and vertical sampling relative to the 2×2 "square" of the original input size.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] With interlaced material, 4:2:0 chroma subsampling can result in motion artifacts if it is implemented the same way as for progressive material.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] The luma samples are derived from separate time intervals, while the chroma samples would be derived from both time intervals.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] It is this difference that can result in motion artifacts.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] The MPEG-2 standard allows for an alternate interlaced sampling scheme, where 4:2:0 is applied to each field (not both fields at once).
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] This solves the problem of motion artifacts, reduces the vertical chroma resolution by half, and can introduce comb-like artifacts in the image.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] The moving text has some motion blur applied to it.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] 4:2:0 **progressive** sampling applied to moving *interlaced* material.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] The chroma leads and trails the moving text.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] 4:2:0 **interlaced** sampling applied to moving *interlaced* material.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] In the 4:2:0 interlaced scheme, however, vertical resolution of the chroma is roughly halved, since the chroma samples effectively describe an area 2 samples wide by 4 samples tall instead of 2×2.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] As well, the spatial displacement between both fields can result in the appearance of comb-like chroma artifacts.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] 4:2:0 **progressive** sampling applied to a still image.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] 4:2:0 **interlaced** sampling applied to a still image.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] If the interlaced material is to be de-interlaced, the comb-like chroma artifacts (from 4:2:0 interlaced sampling) can be removed by blurring the chroma vertically.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] This ratio is possible, and some codecs support it, but it is not widely used.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] This ratio uses half of the vertical and one-fourth the horizontal color resolutions, with only one-eighth of the bandwidth of the maximum color resolutions used.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Uncompressed video in this format with 8-bit quantization uses 10 bytes for every macropixel (which is 4×2 pixels) or 10 bit for every pixel.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] It has the equivalent chrominance bandwidth of a PAL-I or PAL-M signal decoded with a delay line decoder, and still very much superior to NTSC.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Used by Sony in their HDCAM High Definition recorders (not HDCAM SR).
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] In the horizontal dimension, luma is sampled horizontally at three quarters of the full HD sampling rate – 1440 samples per row instead of 1920.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Chroma is sampled at 480 samples per row, a third of the luma sampling rate.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] In the vertical dimension, both luma and chroma are sampled at the full HD sampling rate (1080 samples vertically).
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] A number of legacy schemes allow different subsampling factors in Cb and Cr, similar to how a different amount of bandwidth is allocated to the two chroma values in broadcast systems such as CCIR System M.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] These schemes are not expressible in *J:a:b* notation.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Instead, they adopt a *Y:Cb:Cr* notation, with each part describing the amount of resolution for the corresponding component.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] It is unspecified whether the resolution reduction happens in the horizontal or vertical direction.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Original image without color subsampling.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Note the bleeding in lightness near the borders.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Chroma subsampling suffers from two main types of artifacts, causing degradation more noticeable than intended where colors change abruptly.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Gamma-corrected signals like Y'CbCr have an issue where chroma errors "bleed" into luma.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] In those signals, a low chroma actually makes a color appear less bright than one with equivalent luma.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] As a result, when a saturated color blends with an unsaturated or complementary color, a loss of luminance occurs at the border.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] This can be seen in the example between magenta and green.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] This issue persists in HDR video where gamma is generalized into a transfer function "EOTF".
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] A steeper EOTF shows a stronger luminance loss.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] 2020 defines a "constant luminance" Yc'CbcCrc, which is calculated from linear RGB components and then gamma-encoded.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] This version does not suffer from the luminance loss by design.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Another artifact that can occur with chroma subsampling is that out-of-gamut colors can occur upon chroma reconstruction.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Suppose the image consisted of alternating 1-pixel red and black lines and the subsampling omitted the chroma for the black pixels.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Chroma from the red pixels will be reconstructed onto the black pixels, causing the new pixels to have positive red and *negative* green and blue values.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] As displays cannot output negative light (negative light does not exist), these negative values will effectively be clipped, and the resulting luma value will be too high.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Other sub-sampling filters (especially the averaging "box") have a similar issue that is harder to make a simple example out of.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Similar artifacts arise in the less artificial example of gradation near a fairly sharp red/black boundary.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] It is possible for the decoder to deal with out-of-gamut colors by considering how much chroma a given luma value can hold and distribute it into the 4:4:4 intermediate accordingly, termed "in-range chroma reconstruction" by Glenn Chan.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] The "proportion" method is in spirit similar to Kornelski's luma-weighted average, while the "spill" method resembles error diffusion.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Improving chroma reconstruction remains an active field of research.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] The term Y'UV refers to an analog TV encoding scheme (ITU-R Rec.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] BT.470) while Y'CbCr refers to a digital encoding scheme.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] One difference between the two is that the scale factors on the chroma components (U, V, Cb, and Cr) are different.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] However, the term YUV is often used erroneously to refer to Y'CbCr encoding.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Hence, expressions like "4:2:2 YUV" always refer to 4:2:2 Y'CbCr, since there simply is no such thing as 4:x:x in analog encoding (such as YUV).
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Pixel formats used in Y'CbCr can be referred to as YUV too, for example yuv420p, yuvj420p and many others.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] In a similar vein, the term luminance and the symbol Y are often used erroneously to refer to luma, which is denoted with the symbol Y'.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] The *luma* (Y') of video engineering deviates from the *luminance* (Y) of color science (as defined by CIE).
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Luma is formed as the weighted sum of *gamma-corrected* (tristimulus) RGB components.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Luminance is formed as a weighed sum of *linear* (tristimulus) RGB components.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] In practice, the CIE symbol Y is often incorrectly used to denote luma.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] In 1993, SMPTE adopted Engineering Guideline EG 28, clarifying the two terms.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] The prime symbol ' is used to indicate gamma correction.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Similarly, the chroma of video engineering differs from the chrominance of color science.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] The chroma of video engineering is formed from weighted tristimulus components (gamma corrected, OETF), not linear components.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] In video engineering practice, the terms *chroma*, *chrominance*, and *saturation* are often used interchangeably to refer to chroma, but it is not a good practice, as ITU-T Rec H.273 says.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Chroma subsampling was developed in the 1950s by Alda Bedford for the development of color television by RCA, which developed into the NTSC standard; luma–chroma separation was developed earlier, in 1938 by Georges Valensi.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chroma-subsampling] Through studies, he showed that the human eye has high resolution only for black and white, somewhat less for "mid-range" colors like yellows and greens, and much less for colors on the end of the spectrum, reds and blues.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chrominance] In composite video signals, the U and V signals modulate a color subcarrier signal, and the result is referred to as the chrominance signal; the phase and amplitude of this modulated chrominance signal correspond approximately to the hue and saturation of the color.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chrominance] In digital-video and still-image color spaces such as Y′CbCr, the luma and chrominance components are digital sample values.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chrominance] Separating RGB color signals into luma and chrominance allows the bandwidth of each to be determined separately.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chrominance] Typically, the chrominance bandwidth is reduced in analog composite video by reducing the bandwidth of a modulated color subcarrier, and in digital systems by chroma subsampling.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chrominance] The idea of transmitting a color television signal with distinct luma and chrominance components originated with Georges Valensi, who patented the idea in 1938.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chrominance] Previous schemes for color television systems, which were incompatible with existing monochrome receivers, transmitted RGB signals in various ways.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chrominance] In analog television, chrominance is encoded into a video signal using a subcarrier frequency.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chrominance] Depending on the video standard, the chrominance subcarrier may be either quadrature-amplitude-modulated (NTSC and PAL) or frequency-modulated (SECAM).
[src:chroma-subsampling/chrominance] In the PAL system, the color subcarrier is 4.43 MHz above the video carrier, while in the NTSC system it is 3.58 MHz above the video carrier.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chrominance] The NTSC and PAL standards are the most commonly used, although there are other video standards that employ different subcarrier frequencies.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chrominance] For example, PAL-M (Brazil) uses a 3.58 MHz subcarrier, and SECAM uses two different frequencies, 4.250 MHz and 4.40625 MHz above the video carrier.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chrominance] The presence of chrominance in a video signal is indicated by a color burst signal transmitted on the back porch, just after horizontal synchronization and before each line of video starts.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chrominance] If the color burst signal were visible on a television screen, it would appear as a vertical strip of a very dark olive color.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chrominance] In NTSC and PAL, hue is represented by a phase shift of the chrominance signal relative to the color burst, while saturation is determined by the amplitude of the subcarrier.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chrominance] In SECAM (R′ − Y′) and (B′ − Y′) signals are transmitted alternately and phase does not matter.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chrominance] Chrominance is represented by the U-V color plane in PAL and SECAM video signals, and by the I-Q color plane in NTSC.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chrominance] Digital video and digital still photography systems sometimes use a luma/chroma decomposition for improved compression.
[src:chroma-subsampling/chrominance] On decompression, the Y′CbCr space is rotated back to RGB.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] A **color space** is a specific organization of colors.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] In combination with color profiling supported by various physical devices, it supports reproducible representations of color – whether such representation entails an analog or a digital representation.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] A "color space" is a useful conceptual tool for understanding the color capabilities of a particular device or digital file.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] When trying to reproduce color on another device, color spaces can show whether shadow/highlight detail and color saturation can be retained, and by how much either will be compromised.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] Adding a specific mapping function between a color model and a reference color space establishes within the reference color space a definite "footprint", known as a *gamut*, and for a given color model, this defines a color space.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] For example, Adobe RGB and sRGB are two different absolute color spaces, both based on the RGB color model.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] When defining a color space, the usual reference standard is the CIELAB or CIEXYZ color spaces, which were specifically designed to encompass all colors the average human can see.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] Since "color space" identifies a particular combination of the color model and the mapping function, the word is often used informally to identify a color model.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] However, even though identifying a color space automatically identifies the associated color model, this usage is incorrect in a strict sense.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] For example, although several specific color spaces are based on the RGB color model, there is no such thing as the singular RGB color space.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] In 1802, Thomas Young postulated the existence of three types of photoreceptors (now known as cone cells) in the eye, each of which was sensitive to a particular range of visible light.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] Hermann von Helmholtz developed the Young–Helmholtz theory further in 1850: that the three types of cone photoreceptors could be classified as short-preferring (blue), middle-preferring (green), and long-preferring (red), according to their response to the wavelengths of light striking the retina.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] The relative strengths of the signals detected by the three types of cones are interpreted by the brain as a visible color.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] But it is not clear that they thought of colors as being points in color space.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] The color-space concept was likely due to Hermann Grassmann, who developed it in two stages.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] First, he developed the idea of vector space, which allowed the algebraic representation of geometric concepts in *n*-dimensional space.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] With this conceptual background, in 1853, Grassmann published a theory of how colors mix; it and its three color laws are still taught, as Grassmann's law.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] Colors can be created in printing with color spaces based on the CMYK color model, using the subtractive primary colors of pigment (**c**yan, **m**agenta, **y**ellow, and **k**ey [black]).
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] To create a three-dimensional representation of a given color space, we can assign the amount of magenta color to the representation's X axis, the amount of cyan to its Y axis, and the amount of yellow to its Z axis.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] The resulting 3-D space provides a unique position for every possible color that can be created by combining those three pigments.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] Colors can be created on computer monitors with color spaces based on the RGB color model, using the additive primary colors (red, green, and blue).
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] A three-dimensional representation would assign each of the three colors to the X, Y, and Z axes.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] Colors generated on a given monitor will be limited by the reproduction medium, such as the phosphor (in a CRT monitor) or filters and backlight (LCD monitor).
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] Another way of creating colors on a monitor is with an HSL or HSV color model, based on hue, saturation, brightness (value/lightness).
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] With such a model, the variables are assigned to cylindrical coordinates.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] Many color spaces can be represented as three-dimensional values in this manner, but some have more, or fewer dimensions, and some, such as Pantone, cannot be represented in this way at all.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] Color space conversion is the translation of the representation of a color from one basis to another.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] This typically occurs in the context of converting an image that is represented in one color space to another color space, the goal being to make the translated image look as similar as possible to the original.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] The RGB color model is implemented in different ways, depending on the capabilities of the system used.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] The most common incarnation in general use as of 2021 is the 24-bit implementation, with 8 bits, or 256 discrete levels of color per channel.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] Any color space based on such a 24-bit RGB model is thus limited to a range of 256×256×256 ≈ 16.7 million colors.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] Some implementations use 16 bits per component for 48 bits total, resulting in the same gamut with a larger number of distinct colors.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] This is especially important when working with wide-gamut color spaces (where most of the more common colors are located relatively close together), or when a large number of digital filtering algorithms are used consecutively.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] The same principle applies for any color space based on the same color model, but implemented at different bit depths.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] CIE 1931 XYZ color space was one of the first attempts to produce a color space based on measurements of human color perception (earlier efforts were by James Clerk Maxwell, König & Dieterici, and Abney at Imperial College) and it is the basis for almost all other color spaces.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] The CIERGB color space is a linearly-related companion of CIE XYZ.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] Additional derivatives of CIE XYZ include the CIELUV, CIEUVW, and CIELAB.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] RGB uses additive color mixing, because it describes what kind of *light* needs to be *emitted* to produce a given color.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] RGB stores individual values for red, green and blue.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] RGBA is RGB with an additional channel, alpha, to indicate transparency.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] Common color spaces based on the RGB model include sRGB, Adobe RGB, ProPhoto RGB, scRGB, and CIE RGB.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] CMYK uses subtractive color mixing used in the printing process, because it describes what kind of inks need to be applied so the light *reflected* from the substrate and through the inks produces a given color.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] One starts with a white substrate (canvas, page, etc.), and uses ink to subtract color from white to create an image.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] CMYK stores ink values for cyan, magenta, yellow and black.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] There are many CMYK color spaces for different sets of inks, substrates, and press characteristics (which change the dot gain or transfer function for each ink and thus change the appearance).
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] YIQ was formerly used in NTSC (North America, Japan and elsewhere) television broadcasts for historical reasons.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] This system stores a luma value roughly analogous to (and sometimes incorrectly identified as) luminance, along with two chroma values as approximate representations of the relative amounts of blue and red in the color.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] It is similar to the YUV scheme used in most video capture systems and in PAL (Australia, Europe, except France, which uses SECAM) television, except that the YIQ color space is rotated 33° with respect to the YUV color space and the color axes are swapped.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] The YDbDr scheme used by SECAM television is rotated in another way.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] It is most commonly seen in its digital form, YCbCr, used widely in video and image compression schemes such as MPEG and JPEG.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] xvYCC is an international digital video color space standard published by the IEC (IEC 61966-2-4).
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] It is based on the ITU BT.601 and BT.709 standards but extends the gamut beyond the R/G/B primaries specified in those standards.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] HSV (**h**ue, **s**aturation, **v**alue), also known as HSB (hue, saturation, **b**rightness) is often used by artists because it is often more natural to think about a color in terms of hue and saturation than in terms of additive or subtractive color components.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] HSV is a transformation of an RGB color space, and its components and colorimetry are relative to the RGB color space from which it was derived.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] HSL (**h**ue, **s**aturation, **l**ightness/**l**uminance), also known as HLS or HSI (hue, saturation, **i**ntensity) is quite similar to HSV, with "lightness" replacing "brightness".
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] The difference is that the *brightness* of a pure color is equal to the brightness of white, while the *lightness* of a pure color is equal to the lightness of a medium gray.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] They largely ignored blue light because the added complexity of a 3-component process provided only a marginal increase in fidelity when compared to the jump from monochrome to 2-component color.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] In this article, we concentrate on the second definition.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] CIEXYZ, sRGB, and ICtCp are examples of absolute color spaces, as opposed to a generic RGB color space.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] A non-absolute color space can be made absolute by defining its relationship to absolute colorimetric quantities.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] For instance, if the red, green, and blue colors in a monitor are measured exactly, together with other properties of the monitor, then RGB values on that monitor can be considered as absolute.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] The CIE 1976 L*, a*, b* color space is sometimes referred to as absolute, though it also needs a white point specification to make it so.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] A popular way to make a color space like RGB into an absolute color is to define an ICC profile, which contains the attributes of the RGB.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] This is not the only way to express an absolute color, but it is the standard in many industries.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] RGB colors defined by widely accepted profiles include sRGB and Adobe RGB.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] The process of adding an ICC profile to a graphic or document is sometimes called *tagging* or *embedding*; tagging, therefore, marks the absolute meaning of colors in that graphic or document.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] A color in one absolute color space can be converted into another absolute color space, and back again, in general; however, some color spaces may have gamut limitations, and converting colors that lie outside that gamut will not produce correct results.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] There are also likely to be rounding errors, especially if the popular range of only 256 distinct values per component (8-bit color) is used.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] One part of the definition of an absolute color space is the viewing conditions.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] The same color, viewed under different natural or artificial lighting conditions, will look different.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] Those involved professionally with color matching may use viewing rooms, lit by standardized lighting.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] Occasionally, there are precise rules for converting between non-absolute color spaces.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] For example, HSL and HSV spaces are defined as mappings of RGB.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] Both are non-absolute, but the conversion between them should maintain the same color.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] However, in general, converting between two non-absolute color spaces (for example, RGB to CMYK) or between absolute and non-absolute color spaces (for example, RGB to L*a*b*) is almost a meaningless concept.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] A different method of defining absolute color spaces is familiar to many consumers as the swatch card, used to select paint, fabrics, and the like.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] This is a way of agreeing a color between two parties.
[src:chroma-subsampling/color-space] A more standardized method of defining absolute colors is the Pantone Matching System, a proprietary system that includes swatch cards and recipes that commercial printers can use to make inks that are a particular color.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] In video, **luma** ( $Y'$ ) represents the brightness in an image (the "black-and-white" or achromatic portion of the image).
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] Luma represents the achromatic image, while the chroma components represent the color information.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] Luma is the weighted sum of gamma-compressed R′G′B′ components of a color video—the prime symbols ′ denote gamma compression.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] The word was proposed to prevent confusion between luma as implemented in video engineering and relative luminance as used in color science (i.e. as defined by CIE).
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] Relative luminance is formed as a weighted sum of *linear* RGB components, not gamma-compressed ones.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] Even so, luma is sometimes erroneously called luminance.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] SMPTE EG 28 recommends the symbol $Y'$ to denote luma and the symbol Y to denote relative luminance.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] While luma is more often encountered, relative luminance is sometimes used in video engineering when referring to the brightness of a monitor.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] The formula used to calculate relative luminance uses coefficients based on the CIE color matching functions and the relevant standard chromaticities of red, green, and blue (e.g., the original NTSC primaries, SMPTE C, or Rec.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] The formula used to calculate luma in the Rec.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] where the prime symbol ′ denotes gamma compression.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] Formats following ITU-R Recommendation **BT.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] These coefficients correspond to the SMPTE RP 145 primaries (also known as "SMPTE C") in use at the time the standard was created.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] The change in the luma coefficients is to provide the "theoretically correct" coefficients that reflect the corresponding standard chromaticities ('colors') of the primaries red, green, and blue.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] However, there is some controversy regarding this decision.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] The difference in luma coefficients requires that component signals must be converted between Rec.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] In consumer equipment, the matrix required to perform this conversion may be omitted (to reduce cost), resulting in inaccurate color.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] Image after color subsampling - Error in luminance can be seen as a dark band between Green and Magenta.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] 709 luma coefficients may not necessarily provide better performance.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] Because of the difference between luma and relative luminance, luma does not exactly represent the luminance in an image.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] As a result, errors in chroma can affect luminance.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] Luma alone does not perfectly represent luminance; accurate luminance requires both accurate luma and chroma.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] Hence, errors in chroma "bleed" into the luminance of an image.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] Due to the widespread usage of chroma subsampling, errors in chroma typically occur when it is lowered in resolution/bandwidth.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] This lowered bandwidth, coupled with high frequency chroma components, can cause visible errors in luminance.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] An example of a high frequency chroma component would be the line between the green and magenta bars of the SMPTE color bars test pattern.
[src:chroma-subsampling/luma-video] Error in luminance can be seen as a dark band that occurs in this area.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] Y′ is the luma component, and CB and CR are the blue-difference and red-difference chroma components.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] Luma Y′ (with prime) is distinguished from luminance Y, meaning that light intensity is nonlinearly encoded based on gamma corrected RGB primaries.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] Y′CbCr color spaces are defined by a mathematical coordinate transformation from an associated RGB primaries and white point.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] If the underlying RGB color space is absolute, the Y′CbCr color space is an absolute color space as well; conversely, if the RGB space is ill-defined, so is Y′CbCr.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The transformation is defined in equations 32, 33 in ITU-T H.273.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] Black and white television was in wide use before color television.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] Due to the number of existing TV sets and cameras, some form of backward compatibility was desired for the new color broadcasts.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] French engineer Georges Valensi developed and patented a system for transmitting RGB color as luma and chroma signals in 1938.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] This would allow existing black and white televisions to process only the luma information and ignore the chroma, essentially packaging a black and white video within the color video.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] Because of this backward compatibility, the system based on Valensi's idea was called compatible color.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] In the same way, a black and white broadcast could be received by a color television without any additional processing circuitry.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] To preserve existing broadcast frequency allocations, the new chroma information was given lower bandwidth than the luma information.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] This is possible because humans are more sensitive to the black-and-white information (see image example to the right).
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] YCbCr and Y′CbCr are a practical approximation to color processing and perceptual uniformity, where the primary colors corresponding roughly to red, green, and blue are processed into perceptually meaningful information.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] By doing this, subsequent image/video processing, transmission and storage can do operations and introduce errors in perceptually meaningful ways.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] Y′CbCr is used to separate out a luma signal (Y′) that can be stored with high resolution or transmitted at high bandwidth and two chroma components (CB and CR) that can be bandwidth-reduced, subsampled, compressed, or otherwise treated separately for improved system efficiency.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] YCbCr is sometimes abbreviated to **YCC**.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] Typically the terms Y′CbCr, YCbCr, YPbPr, and Y′UV are used interchangeably, leading to some confusion.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The main difference is that YPbPr is used with analog images and YCbCr with digital images, leading to different scaling values for Umax and Vmax (in YCbCr both are ${\tfrac {1}{2}}$ ) when converting to/from YUV.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] Y′CbCr and YCbCr differ due to the values being gamma corrected or not.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The equations below give a better picture of the common principles and general differences between these formats.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] where KR, KG, and KB are ordinarily derived from the definition of the corresponding RGB space and required to satisfy $K_{R}+K_{G}+K_{B}=1$ .
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] Here, the prime (′) symbols mean gamma correction is being used; thus R′, G′, and B′ nominally range from 0 to 1, with 0 representing the minimum intensity (e.g., for display of the color black) and 1 the maximum (e.g., for display of the color white).
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The resulting luma (Y) value will then have a nominal range from 0 to 1, and the chroma (PB and PR) values will have a nominal range from -0.5 to +0.5.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The reverse conversion process can be derived by inverting the above equations.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] When representing the signals in digital form, the results are scaled and rounded and offsets are typically added.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] For example, the scaling and offset applied to the Y′ component per specification (e.g.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] MPEG-2) results in the value of 16 for black and the value of 235 for white when using an 8-bit representation.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The standard has 8-bit digitized versions of CB and CR scaled to a different range of 16 to 240.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] Consequently, rescaling by the fraction (235-16)/(240-16) = 219/224 is sometimes required when doing color matrixing or processing in YCbCr space, resulting in quantization distortions when the subsequent processing is not performed using higher bit depths.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The scaling that results in the use of a smaller range of digital values than what might appear to be desirable for representation of the nominal range of the input data allows for some "overshoot" and "undershoot" during processing without necessitating undesirable clipping.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] This "headroom" and "toeroom" (or "footroom") can also be used for extension of the nominal color gamut as specified by xvYCC.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The value 235 accommodates a maximum overshoot of (255 - 235) / (235 - 16) = 9.1%, which is slightly larger than the theoretical maximum overshoot (Gibbs' Phenomenon) of about 8.9% of the maximum (black-to-white) step.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The toeroom is smaller, allowing only 16 / 219 = 7.3% overshoot—here in opposite direction—, which is less than the theoretical maximum overshoot of 8.9%.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] In addition, because values 0 and 255 are reserved in HDMI, the room is actually slightly less.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] This causes some difficulty in determining how to correctly interpret and display some Y′CbCr signals.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] These out-of-range Y′CbCr values are used by xvYCC to encode colors outside the BT.709 gamut.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] From the above constants and formulas, the following can be derived for ITU-R BT.601.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The resultant signals have Y′ (luma) values ranging from 16 to 235, and Cb & Cr (chrominance) values ranging from 16 to 240.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The values from 0 to 15 are called *footroom*, and the values from 236 to 255 are called *headroom*.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The same quantisation ranges, different for Y and Cb, Cr also apply to BT.2020 and BT.709.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] In the formula below, the scaling factors are multiplied by ${\frac {256}{255}}$ .
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] This allows for the value 256 in the denominator, which can be calculated by a single bitshift.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] If the R'd G'd B'd digital source includes footroom and headroom, the footroom offset 16 needs to be subtracted first from each signal, and a scale factor of ${\frac {255}{219}}$ needs to be included in the equations.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] This form of Y′CbCr is used primarily for older standard-definition television systems, as it uses an RGB model that fits the phosphor emission characteristics of older CRTs.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] A different form of Y′CbCr is specified in the ITU-R BT.709 standard, primarily for HDTV use.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The newer form is also used in some computer-display oriented applications, as sRGB (though the matrix used for sRGB form of YCbCr, sYCC, is still BT.601).
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] In this case, the values of Kb and Kr differ, but the formulas for using them are the same.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] This form of Y′CbCr is based on an RGB model that more closely fits the phosphor emission characteristics of newer CRTs and other modern display equipment.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The definitions of the R', G', and B' signals also differ between BT.709 and BT.601, differ within BT.601 depending on the type of TV system in use (625-line as in PAL and SECAM or 525-line as in NTSC), and differ further in other specifications.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] So proper conversion of Y′CbCr from one form to the other is not just a matter of inverting one matrix and applying the other.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The ITU-R BT.2020 standard uses the same gamma function as BT.709.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The encoding conversion can, as usual, be written as a matrix.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The smaller values in the matrix are not rounded; they are precise values.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] For systems with limited precision (8 or 10 bit, for example) a lower precision of the above matrix could be used, for example, retaining only 6 digits after the decimal point.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The CL function can be used when preservation of luminance is of primary importance (see: Chroma subsampling § Gamma luminance error), or when "there is an expectation of improved coding efficiency for delivery." The specification refers to Report ITU-R BT.2246 on this matter.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] BT.2246 states that CL has improved compression efficiency and luminance preservation, but NCL will be more familiar to a staff that has previously handled color mixing and other production practices in HDTV YCbCr.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] BT.2020 does not define PQ and thus HDR; it is further defined in SMPTE ST 2084 and BT.2100.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] BT.2100 will introduce the use of ICTCP, a semi-perceptual colorspace derived from linear RGB with good hue linearity.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] JFIF usage of JPEG supports a modified Rec.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] 601 Y′CbCr, where Y′, CB, and CR have the full 8-bit range of [0...255].
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] Below are the conversion equations expressed to six decimal digits of precision.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] (For ideal equations, see ITU-T T.871.) Note that for the following formula, the range of each input (R,G,B) is also the full 8-bit range of [0...255].
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The above conversion is identical to sYCC when the input is given as sRGB, except that IEC 61966-2-1:1999/Amd1:2003 only gives four decimal digits.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] JPEG also defines a "YCCK" format from Adobe for CMYK input.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] In this format, the "K" value is passed as-is, while CMY are used to derive YCbCr with the above matrix by assuming $R=1-C$ , $G=1-M$ , and $B=1-Y$ .
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] As a result, a similar set of subsampling techniques can be used.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] Another example was P3-D65 primaries used by Netflix in production with BT.2020-NCL matrix, which means matrix was not derived from primaries, nowadays though Netflix allows BT.2020 primaries (after 2021).
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] General users of Netflix did not ever get that mezzanine format though.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] Prior to the development of fast SIMD floating-point processors, most digital implementations of RGB → Y′UV used integer math, in particular fixed-point approximations.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] Approximation means that the precision of the used numbers (input data, output data and constant values) is limited, and thus a precision loss of typically about the last binary digit is accepted by whoever makes use of that option in typically a trade-off to improved computation speeds.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] Y′ values are conventionally shifted and scaled to the range [16, 235] (referred to as studio swing or "TV levels") rather than using the full range of [0, 255] (referred to as full swing or "PC levels").
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] This practice was standardized in SMPTE-125M in order to accommodate signal overshoots ("ringing") due to filtering.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] U and V values, which may be positive or negative, are summed with 128 to make them always positive, giving a studio range of 16–240 for U and V.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] These matrices round all factors to the closest 1/256 unit.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] As a result, only one 16-bit intermediate value is formed for each component, and a simple right-shift with rounding `(x + 128) >> 8` can take care of the division.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] Google's Skia used to use the above 8-bit full-range matrix, resulting in a slight greening effect on JPEG images encoded by Android devices, more noticeable on repeated saving.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The issue was fixed in 2016, when the more accurate version was used instead.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] Due to SIMD optimizations in libjpeg-turbo, the accurate version is actually faster.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] RGB data are typically encoded at 8, 12, 16, or 24 bits per pixel.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] In the examples below, 24-bit RGB is assumed; this format is commonly denoted RGB888.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] In the standard byte order, the data are stored as `r0, g0, b0, r1, g1, b1, ...`.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] YCbCr packed pixel formats are often referred to as "Y′UV".
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] Such files can be encoded in 12, 16 or 24 bits per pixel.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] Depending on subsampling, the formats can largely be described as 4:2:0p, 4:2:2, and 4:4:4.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The apostrophe after the Y is often omitted, as is the "p" (for planar) after YUV420p.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] In terms of actual file formats, 4:2:0 is the most common, as the data is more reduced, and the file extension is usually `.YUV`.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The relation between data rate and sampling (A:B:C) is defined by the ratio between Y to U and V channel.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The notation of "YUV" followed by three numbers is vague: the three numbers could refer to the subsampling (as is done in "YUV420"), or it could refer to bit depth in each channel (as is done in "YUV565").
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] The unambiguous way to refer to these formats is via the FourCC code.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] To convert from RGB to YUV or back, it is simplest to use RGB888 and 4:4:4.
[src:chroma-subsampling/ycbcr] There are also "tiled" variants of planar formats.
